I was interested to compare the performance of quad core CPUS in the T400.
I only compared the Q9100 and QX9300 against the T9800.
The T9800 is the fastest dual core you can get with the T400.

I used [sysbench](https://github.com/akopytov/sysbench) for all of these benchmarks.
As far as I understand, sysbench simply runs a PRNG and counts the number of numbers generated per second (events per second).
For each CPU, I ran the benchmark for 300 seconds with 4 threads then another 300 seconds with 2 threads.
I generated the charts and tables by averaging the relevant data for each of the benchmarks.

The main tests were all done on the same T400 with the ATI graphics heatsink and the cooling mod.
The main test machine was using Parabola/XFCE with XFCE's power manager running.
I believe the test machine I set up is representative of a "normal" linux environment.
I then compared the performance of the Q9100 and the QX9300 on my main machine runnig Void/BSPWM with no power management other than powertop.
It turns out that by not using the power manager, the QX9300 completely swamps the competition.

The main takeaways seem to be as follows:

+ Power managers are now sophisticated enough that the quad-core CPUs are plug-and-play, albeit with a significant performance reduction.
+ The quads don't get particularly hot, even without a DE power manager
+ The quads use significantly more power than the duos.

## Full Data for Nerds

I used this script to gather all of the data presented above:
```bash

#!/bin/bash
# Script requires: sysbench gawk bash powerstat

rm bench.log >/dev/null 2>&1

runtime=300
interval=2
echo "starting benchmark"

Bench(){
 sysbench cpu --threads=$threads --time=$runtime --report-interval=$interval run
}

Get_info(){
while read -r line; do
 case $line in
  \[*s*\]*)
    power=$(awk '{print $1*10^-6 "W"}' /sys/class/power_supply/BAT1/power_now)
    bench=$(awk '/\[.*\]/ {print $2 " " $7}' <<<$line)
    temp=$(awk '{print substr($1,0,length($1)-3) "°"}' /sys/class/thermal/thermal_zone0/temp)
    printf "%s\n" "$bench $temp $power"
 esac
done
}

Run(){
Bench | Get_info >> bench.log
}

sleep 2
(sleep $((interval+1)) && tail -f bench.log) &
threads=4
echo "running with 4 threads"
Run
threads=2
echo "running with 2 threads"
Run
kill 0
```
